content.description: Sit start with right hand in blast hole and left hand on side pull go straight up to top
content.location: Large rock wall just before seagull outfitter (on the right if going down gunflint on left if heading towards grand Marais.

content.description: start the far right side of the wall on a head night ledge. Work all the way left until you get to the starting holds of dihidie. (Can be done Left to right but is slightly harder)
content.location: On the far right of seagull wall

content.description: Squat start and move up through the exposed blast hole using it as a hand jam. Sketchy top out, be carful to not fall onto the boulders to the right of the problem.
content.location: In the middle of the seagull wall.

content.description: Either nobody climbs here or there’s a reason nobody climbs here. Rock is very loose or crumbly all across the bluff. All potential routes are unclean and potentially dangerous of rock fall. DO NOT belay from below. Not a place for unseasoned climbers.
content.location: HoneyMoon Bluff at the east end of Hungry Jack Lake off the Gunflint Trail. Easy to find, google it. Short approach from parking lot. At the lookout on the other side of the railing. Left of center look out point. Short and sweet little sustained leaning ledge climb.

content.description: Start on good side pull jug. Use decent feet to struggle up a straight crimp rail. Find feet and dyno to a very bad sloping dish right under the top. Find feet again and do a big move to the top out or go for decent edges and add a few extra moves. Very easy mantle top out
content.location: Around the corner that magnetic arete is on. Only one way to climb this section of the boulder. Very aesthetic route

content.description: This is a placeholder for Magnetic Rock.  A large exposed glacial rock formation 1.5 miles from the Gunflint Trail on "Magetic Lake" hiking trail.  I was unable to complete this send as I did not hike this trail with the proper gear.  The photo is of me just playing around.  The rating is a complete guess for the face in the photo.  There are lots of possibilities here.  If anyone has any information regarding this rock or climbing it please let me know.
content.protection: Lots of cracks.  Stoppers and Hexes smaller than fist size should work.  Or some good crash pads.
content.location: Take the Gunflint Trail North to the "Magnetic Lake" trailhead on the Right side of road.  Hike the trail 1.5 miles through some rocky, but well established terrain.  Very fun approach!

content.description: Crux is definitely the opening moves. Start on single pad crimps. Gain a good foot under bulge with left and heel hook arete with right. Throw for knobs with right and match with left. Pull yourself over the bulge and walk easy slab up. Was V4 until new easy beta was found. Fun problem! Good warm up
content.protection: 2 pads. Has a good landing. Watch for crumbly rock at the top
content.location: Same boulder as "in the time of chimpanzees"  obvious bulging arete that you can see from the approach

content.description: Start low and use side pull and undercling to throw for the horizontal crack.
content.location: Slightly past magnetic rock trail. (On the right side if going to trails end, on left if going to grand Marais.)

content.description: Getting to the sloping rail is crux on this one. Start left hand on crimp right hand on good flat ledge. Jump from top to other boulder just below top out
content.protection: 2 large pads or 3+ small ones. One on ground and 1 on large boulder below top out. Confident spotters
content.location: Magnetic lake, superior national forest. Up the Gunflint trail. Go to Gunflint lodge, paddle to magnetic or rent a motor boat from Gunflint. Through narrows across lake then to west bay on magnetic. Obvious boulder 20 yards inland from lake. Project on back side. Easy access to boulder from lake. 25 minute approach in motor boat. 1 hour in canoe. Start on obvious feature with left and good ledge on right. Starts on west side face of boulder

content.description: Stand start underneath the detached rock that looks like an arrow and move straight up to the top out.
content.location: On the Right side of the seagull wall.

content.description:
Either nobody climbed here or there’s a reason nobody climbs here. Rock is very loose or crumbly all across the bluff. All potential routes are unclean and potentially dangerous of rock fall. DO NOT belay from below. Not a place for unseasoned climbers.

 This route has a nice lie back roof move. Drop down to obvious ledge below. Not worth going any lower into the rotting rock section.
content.protection: Cams, nuts, cord, all the essentials for a solid top rope set up
content.location: HoneyMoon Bluff at the east end of Hungry Jack Lake off the Gunflint Trail. Easy to find, google it. Short approach from parking lot. At the lookout on the other side of the railing. “Center-ish-right”

content.description: Stand start and move straight up into dihedral and top out.
content.location: on the left side of seagull wall

climbs.name: Crimpin aint easy (but it sho is fun)

content.description: Start on under cling side pull jug. Good feet directly under start. Shoot up with left hand to crimp then gain right hand crimp. Adjust feet and Gaston to decent crimp with left. Do a funky mantle move to gain good right foot. Slowly reach for another right handed crimp. Move left hand up crimping rail and smear with left foot. Big move to decent slopes. Gain wide feet and do another big move to 2 pad crease on top out. Easy mantle top out
content.protection: 2 pads over rocks at base of problem
content.location: Same boulder as magnetic arete and in the time of chimpanzees. Directly to the left of magnetic arete

content.description: Start same as crimpin ain't easy. Grain decent crimp in left and match. High feet lead you to a big left hand throw to bad sloping crimp thing. For balance Gaston on poor sloper under your left hand. Bring left foot up to good edge and the Gaston with right hand again to decent crimp. Throw your right foot over the bulge and try to find good feet. Drop left foot and bump left hand up above your right hand to another poor crimp. Reach way out to poor sloping seem with right and compress your way up to a scary stand. At this point you have to smear with hands and feet and find your way up the tall slab. Best problem in the area so far!
content.protection: 4+ pads. I did it with 2 trifold metolious pads but some of the dead logs that make the fall dangerous weren't covered. Suck it up and go for it!
content.location: Variation to crimpin ain't easy. Same corner to the left of magnetic arete.

climbs.name: Batchelor Party at The Bowling Ally

content.description:
Either nobody climbed here or there’s a reason nobody climbs here. Rock is very loose or crumbly all across the bluff. All potential routes are unclean and potentially dangerous of rock fall. DO NOT belay from below. Not a place for unseasoned climbers. Top rope set up. Route starts at the very bottom and climbs up onto lower dihedral, vertical finger crack, one 10- move and continues past standing resting ledge up 5.9- 

 There is a good potential rock face crack system left of this line on lower ledge.
content.location: HoneyMoon Bluff at the east end of Hungry Jack Lake off the Gunflint Trail. Easy to find, google it. Short approach from parking lot. At the lookout on the other side of the railing to the far left (south).

content.description:
Wind your way through 57 miles of beautiful boreal forests, past glacial Gunflint Trail lakes, and through outdoor splendor where the only human habitation takes place at camp sites.(taken from gunflint site) 

  There is plenty of undiscovered climbing here.  The ecosystem is very void of human contact(like many climbing areas).  Please respect the environment when scouting new terrain.  Happy exploring!
